to drive there on a motorbike. Yes, on a motorbike with LIFE. At times it seemed quite peaceful riding there, until grown men without scarfs driving trailers, boys on rickshaw bikes, and women and their mounds of goods passed by. I could feel their hot breath on my face as if I was right there with them. We drove down these narrow scary streets (not quite as scary as Ghana but just as crazy) as people just tried to navigate around us to get back to their destinations and are ready for their afternoon break. It is good tensioning for the brain and body to battle this life everyday.

We made it to the grocery store to get a few things like bread and tortillas, since the price of them here is so cheap. This is in part due to cheap of gas in Ghana. We made our purchases, and got right back into the dangerous ride back home. When I finally wanted to put my legs down and didn’t put myself in an awkward position on the bike, I got too close to the chain which caught the back of the sandal from my foot. I must say this time I was a fully different person from the panicking girl that I was in Ghana. I learnt from my experience and handled the situation like a boss.
